"attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barenton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): habitational name primarily from Brenton near Exminster, possibly named in Old English as <i>Brȳningtūn</i> ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) associated with <i>Brȳni</i>’ (a personal name from Old English <i>bryne</i> ‘fire, flame’)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":16,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":29,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Nicholas de Barenton III was born in 1299, in Thriplow, Cambridgeshire, England, his father, Nicholas Barrington Jr, was 59 and his mother, Mrs. Nicholas Barrington, was 54. He had at least 2 sons with Alice Belhouse. He died in 1330, in Essex, England, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1299–1330":"1299–1330","1306–1327":"1306–1327","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1327–1343":"1327–1343","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1240–1272":"1240–1272","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1245":"1245","1299":"1299","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","1330":"1330","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Hatfield Broad Oak, Essex, England":"Hatfield Broad Oak, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Barrington Hall, Thriplow, Cambridgeshire, England":"Thriplow, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"1299–1330":"1299–1330","1306–1327":"1306–1327","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1327–1343":"1327–1343","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1240–1272":"1240–1272